  title={Consumer shopping behavior: how much do consumers save?},
  author={Griffith, Rachel and Leibtag, Ephraim and Leicester, Andrew and Nevo, Aviv},
  journal={Journal of Economic Perspectives},
  volume={23},
  number={2},
  pages={99--120},
  year={2009}
}
They look at 4 kinds of discounting behavior (sales, bulk, outlet choice, and generic brands) for a wide range of food products using 2006 Homescan-style data in the UK. My paper is different because it expands to include non-food items. I also compute savings using actual quantities purchased, and explore the underlying reasons contributing to the difference in bulk purchasing. They also find a much smaller difference in bulk buying between income groups and a less monotonic relationship. This could be due to the focus on food products (I also find a smaller gap), but it could potentially be related to the setting. I focus on US grocery expenditures from 2004--2017 and they focus on UK grocery expenditures in 2006. They do highlight that bulk discounts are where households could save the most money (~224 pounds). They also only focus on overall baskets and don't look within stores.

